Fabia in 51 13.c. He was one of the most profligate men of his time, and the cause of constant uneasiness to Cicero. At Pharsalia, and afterwards in Africa and Spain, he fought on the side of Caesar, who in 44 mc. raised him, despite the opposition of Antony, to the consulship. On Caesar’s. death, however, he joined the republican party, but when Antony gave him the province of Syria he became a fierce anti—republican.
